{"key":"post-8511054","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8511054</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;how far superior and simplified is casing from cakes?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The 'casing' is simply the top layer that is placed over the substrate.&amp;nbsp; It has no nutrient value and is only to supply moisture and beneficial organisms.&amp;nbsp; If your casing layer is loose and airy as it should be, it will create little air pockets of high humidity that can help stimulate pinning.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You'll still need to colonize cakes or grains as spawn to inoculate your bulk substrates, that you'll later case if desired.&amp;nbsp; Casing layers benefit cubensis very little if you're good at managing light, moisture, and air exchange.&amp;nbsp; With soaking/dunking, casing layers have become obsolete, in my opinion.&amp;nbsp; Some species won't fruit without a casing layer, but &lt;i&gt;P cubensis&lt;/i&gt; isn't in that catagory.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Many old hands still swear by them, but if you'll manage your substrate properly, you can achieve the same end results uncased.&amp;nbsp; You'll have fewer fruits, but they'll be larger.&amp;nbsp; A properly maintained casing layer can produce&amp;nbsp; wall to wall fruits, but they'll be smaller.&amp;nbsp; Overall yields hardly change.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8511189</next>\n<prev>8510999</prev>\n<first>8509664</first>\n<last>8513681</last>\n<when>1213208233</when>\n<utime>06/11/08 09:17 PM</utime>\n</post>"}